(88, 1, '2014-11-13 09:21:25', '2014-11-13 09:21:25', '<div id="slide_20">\r\n<h1>Journey to the bottom of the Iceberg?</h1>\r\n<h3 class="red" style="text-align: center;">1 Fatal accident</h3>\r\n<h3 style="text-align: center;">10 Non-fatal accidents</h3>\r\n<h3 style="text-align: center;">30 Reportable incidents</h3>\r\n<h4 style="text-align: center;">Incidents are rehearsals for accidents - we can learn from them if our culture allows us to</h4>\r\n<h2 style="text-align: center;">00âs unsafe acts</h2>\r\n<h5>Source: Heinrich</h5>\r\n</div>', 'Slide 20 - ICEBERG ', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-20-iceberg', '', '', '2014-11-14 08:30:01', '2014-11-14 08:30:01', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=88', 19, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(89, 1, '2014-11-13 09:21:42', '2014-11-13 09:21:42', '', 'Slide 21 - ICEBERG - Question', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-21-iceberg-question', '', '', '2014-11-14 08:40:35', '2014-11-14 08:40:35', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=89', 20, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(90, 1, '2014-11-13 09:21:57', '2014-11-13 09:21:57', '<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>An incorrect fitting of a part that can be fitted in a number of different ways\r\n<i><span class="reddish">- Why report :</span> <span class="blueish">amend design to âMurphy Proofâ</span></i>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Inaccurate, incomplete or confusing technical instructions\r\n<i><span class="reddish">- Why report :</span> <span class="blueish"> amend the instructions to prevent others getting it wrong</span></i>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Lack of spares, tools & equipment (only after giving management the opportunity to resolve)\r\n<i><span class="reddish">- Why report :</span> <span class="blueish"> to ensure resources are provided</span></i>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>An honest mistake youâve made whilst undertaking manufacturing activities\r\n<i><span class="reddish">- Why report :</span> <span class="blueish"> so others can learn from your mistake</span></i>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Slide 22 - TYPES OF ISSUES TO REPORT', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-22-types-of-issues-to-report', '', '', '2014-11-14 08:46:30', '2014-11-14 08:46:30', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=90', 21, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(91, 1, '2014-11-13 09:22:11', '2014-11-13 09:22:11', '<div class="safety_culture">\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n	<li>The successful implementation of an Error Management System (EMS) will enable managers to maximise their ability to identify, mitigate and manage risks by involving all staff in the reporting and subsequent analysis of potential hazards, system failures and human errors in order to minimise the potential for recurrence.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3 class="blueish" style="text-align: center;"></h3>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3 class="blueish" style="text-align: center;">âTHE LIFEBLOOD OF ANY ERROR MANAGEMENT SYSTEM IS REPORTINGâ</h3>\r\n</div>', 'Slide 23 - ERROR MANAGEMENT SYSTEM ', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-23-error-management-system', '', '', '2014-11-14 08:51:55', '2014-11-14 08:51:55', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=91', 22, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(92, 1, '2014-11-13 09:22:28', '2014-11-13 09:22:28', '<div class="safety_culture">\r\n<img src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_24.png" alt="slide_24" width="547" height="397" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-180" />\r\n</div>', 'Slide 24 - ERROR MANAGEMENT SYSTEM', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-24-error-management-system', '', '', '2014-11-14 08:53:13', '2014-11-14 08:53:13', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=92', 23, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(93, 1, '2014-11-13 09:22:43', '2014-11-13 09:22:43', '<div class="safety_culture">\r\n<h3>The M&CA EMS provides a mechanism to report, investigate and prevent:</h3>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>Maintenance errors</li>\r\n<li>Procedures that are ambiguous or inaccurate</li>\r\n<li>Mismatches between required and actual practices and</li>\r\n<li>Any other condition which could lead to an error (if left unresolved).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>', 'Slide 25 - ERROR MANAGEMENT SYSTEM', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-25-error-management-system', '', '', '2014-11-14 08:55:10', '2014-11-14 08:55:10', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=93', 24, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(94, 1, '2014-11-13 09:23:03', '2014-11-13 09:23:03', '<div class="safety_culture">\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>When an investigation is carried out following an event there is no requirement to establish or apportion blame. </li>\r\n<li>BAE Systems Saudi Arabia recognises that people cannot easily avoid those actions which they did not intend to commit in the first place.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>', 'Slide 26 - ROOT CAUSE ERROR INVESTIGATION ', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-26-root-cause-error-investigation', '', '', '2014-11-14 08:57:31', '2014-11-14 08:57:31', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=94', 25, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(95, 1, '2014-11-13 09:23:17', '2014-11-13 09:23:17', '<div class="safety_culture">\r\n<h3>Error? </h3>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>Where a person should have done other than what they did</li>\r\n<li><b>Unintentional</b></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3>Maintenance Error?</h3>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>The maintenance system (which includes people) fails to perform in the manner expected</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>', 'Slide 27 - TYPES OF ERRORS', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-27-types-of-errors', '', '', '2014-11-14 08:59:25', '2014-11-14 08:59:25', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=95', 26, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(96, 1, '2014-11-13 09:23:29', '2014-11-13 09:23:29', '', 'Slide 28 - Question', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-28-question', '', '', '2014-12-01 16:09:25', '2014-12-01 16:09:25', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=96', 27, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(97, 1, '2014-11-13 09:23:57', '2014-11-13 09:23:57', '[row]\r\n[column_8]\r\n<h3>Active failures: </h3>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>Errors having an immediate impact</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/column_8]\r\n[column_4]\r\n<img src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_29-a.png" alt="slide_29-a" width="291" height="202" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-183" />\r\n[/column_4]\r\n[/row]\r\n\r\n[row]\r\n[column_8]\r\n<h3>Latent failures: </h3>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>Errors that lay dormant for a long time </li>\r\n<li>Typically only becoming apparent when they combine with other failures and local triggering events </li>\r\n<li>It is then that an accident occurs, exampleâ¦</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/column_8]\r\n[column_4]\r\n<img src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_29-b.png" alt="slide_29-b" width="293" height="204" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-185" />\r\n[/column_4]\r\n[/row]', 'Slide 29 - TWO TYPES OF ERRORS', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-29-two-types-of-errors', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:07:41', '2014-11-14 09:07:41', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=97', 28, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(98, 1, '2014-11-13 09:24:09', '2014-11-13 09:24:09', '', 'Slide 30 - Question', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-30-question', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:09:31', '2014-11-14 09:09:31', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=98', 29, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(99, 1, '2014-11-13 09:26:23', '2014-11-13 09:26:23', '<div class="safety_culture">\r\n<h3>VIOLATION</h3>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>What caused this and how does it differ from ERROR</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3>INTENTIONAL</h3>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>A human action or behaviour</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h3>THREE TYPES:</h3>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>Organisational Gain- A maintainer engages in a practice that is condoned by management , that bends the rules.</li>\r\n<li>Personal Gain â A maintainer strays from the accepted procedures to save time that bends the rules.</li>\r\n<li>Reckless â A maintainer wilfully breaks standing rules disregarding the consequences.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>', 'Slide 31 - WHAT ELSE MIGHT WE HAVE IF NOT AN ERROR', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-31-what-else-might-we-have-if-not-an-error', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:11:49', '2014-11-14 09:11:49', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=99', 30, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(100, 1, '2014-11-13 09:26:34', '2014-11-13 09:26:34', '', 'Slide 32 - Question', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-32-question', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:13:13', '2014-11-14 09:13:13', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=100', 31, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(101, 1, '2014-11-13 09:26:47', '2014-11-13 09:26:47', '', 'Slide 33 - Question', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-33-question', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:15:40', '2014-11-14 09:15:40', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=101', 32, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(102, 1, '2014-11-13 09:27:02', '2014-11-13 09:27:02', '<div class="safety_culture">\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>BAE Systems Saudi Arabia has the FAiR tool provided by Baines Simmons to look at what has happened post investigations.</li>\r\n<li>Lets take a brief look at this tool ......</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>', 'Slide 34 - TOOLS AVAILABLE TO LOOK AT INCIDENTS ', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-34-tools-available-to-look-at-incidents', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:17:20', '2014-11-14 09:17:20', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=102', 33, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(103, 1, '2014-11-13 09:27:15', '2014-11-13 09:27:15', '<img src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_35.png" alt="slide_35" width="720" height="501" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-188" />', 'Slide 35 - FAiRÂ®', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-35-fair', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:19:46', '2014-11-14 09:19:46', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=103', 34, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(104, 1, '2014-11-13 09:27:28', '2014-11-13 09:27:28', '<img src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_36.png" alt="slide_36" width="720" height="501" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-189" />', 'Slide 36 - FAiRÂ®', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-36-fair', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:19:34', '2014-11-14 09:19:34', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=104', 35, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(105, 1, '2014-11-13 09:27:42', '2014-11-13 09:27:42', '[row]\r\n[column_4]\r\n<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-191" src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_37.png" alt="slide_37" width="183" height="349" />\r\n[/column_4]\r\n[column_8]\r\n&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<h1 style="text-align: center;">THE IMPORTANCE OF HUMAN FACTORS IN THE AERONAUTICAL ENGINEERING WORKPLACE</h1>\r\n[/column_8]\r\n[/row]', 'Slide 37 - IMPORTANCE OF HUMAN FACTORS', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-37-importance-of-human-factors', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:23:20', '2014-11-14 09:23:20', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=105', 36, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(106, 1, '2014-11-13 09:27:56', '2014-11-13 09:27:56', '<div class="safety_culture">\r\n<h3>Applying Human Factors to the workplace can:</h3>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>Reduce the potential for accidents </li>\r\n<li>Reduce the potential for injury and ill health</li>\r\n<li>Improve performance and productivity</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>SO WHAT DO YOU THINK ABOUT THE ABOVE?</h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2 class="blueish">âTHESE ARE ONLY EFFECTIVE IF WE REPORT THE PROBLEMSâ</h2>\r\n\r\n', 'Slide 38 - BENEFITS OF HUMAN FACTORS', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-38-benefits-of-human-factors', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:25:26', '2014-11-14 09:25:26', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=106', 37, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(107, 1, '2014-11-13 09:28:10', '2014-11-13 09:28:10', '', 'Slide 39 - Question', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-39-question', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:26:50', '2014-11-14 09:26:50', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=107', 38, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(108, 1, '2014-11-13 09:28:23', '2014-11-13 09:28:23', '<h2>We work in an environment that produces error:</h2>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>We frequently remove and replace many parts</li>\r\n<li>Sometimes with less than adequate tooling, equipment, parts, knowledge or time</li>\r\n<li>People who write the manuals, work instructions & procedures hardly ever do the job for real</li>\r\n<li>People who start on a job are not necessarily the ones to finish it</li>\r\n<li>Our system requires many people to do their job to enable the last person touching the aircraft to do theirs...</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<img src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_40.png" alt="slide_40" width="410" height="179" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-194" />\r\n', 'Slide 40 - HUMAN FACTORS IN THE ENGINEERING WORKPLACE', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-40-human-factors-in-the-engineering-workplace', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:28:29', '2014-11-14 09:28:29', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=108', 39, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(109, 1, '2014-11-13 09:29:54', '2014-11-13 09:29:54', '[row]\r\n[column_8]\r\n<h3>Likely contributing factors:</h3>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>Fails to use approved data or company procedures</li>\r\n<li>Staff shortages</li>\r\n<li>Time pressures</li>\r\n<li>Errors occur at night</li>\r\n<li>Shift & task handovers</li>\r\n<li>Communication & Reporting breakdown</li>\r\n<li>Supervisors carrying out long hands-on tasks</li>\r\n<li>âCan-doâ attitude</li>\r\n<li>Interruptions</li>\r\n<li>Inadequate pre-planning, equipment or spares.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/column_8]\r\n[column_4]\r\n<img src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_41.png" alt="slide_41" width="152" height="292" class="alignright size-full wp-image-196" />\r\n[/column_4]\r\n[/row]', 'Slide 41 - HUMAN FACTORS AFFECTS ON SAFETY ', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-41-human-factors-affects-on-safety', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:38:31', '2014-11-14 09:38:31', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=109', 40, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(110, 1, '2014-11-13 09:30:07', '2014-11-13 09:30:07', '<h5>Human Factors is also concerned with the âfitâ between people and their work. It puts people first, taking account of their capabilities and limitations. Human Factors aims to make sure that tasks, equipment, information and the environment fit each worker</h5>\r\n\r\n<h4><b>The job / task being done:</b></h4>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>The demands on the worker (activities, workload, work pacing, shift work and fatigue)</li>\r\n<li>The equipment used (its design in terms of size, shape, controls, displays, and how appropriate it is for the task)</li>\r\n<li>The information used (how it is presented, accessed, and changed)</li>\r\n<li>The physical environment (temperature, humidity, lighting, noise and vibration).</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Slide 42 - HUMAN FACTORS', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-42-human-factors', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:41:12', '2014-11-14 09:41:12', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=110', 41, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(111, 1, '2014-11-13 09:30:20', '2014-11-13 09:30:20', '<img src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_43.png" alt="slide_43" width="1668" height="481" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-198" />\r\n<h5>There is only one way to disassemble the nutsâ¦but</h5>\r\n<h5>Over 40,000 wrong ways to reassemble them, not including errors of omission!</h5>', 'Slide 43 - BOLT & NUTS THEORYâ¦â¦', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-43-bolt-nuts-theory', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:42:39', '2014-11-14 09:42:39', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=111', 42, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(112, 1, '2014-11-13 09:30:32', '2014-11-13 09:30:32', '<div id="slide_44">\r\n<div id="slide_44_in">\r\n<h3>Chain of events:</h3>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>Multiple contributing causes that can lead to an accident</li>\r\n<li>Rarely does an accident have a single cause</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>\r\n<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-199" src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_44.png" alt="slide_44" width="1847" height="1160" />\r\n<h3 class="blueish" style="text-align: center;">If we can break just one link in the chain, the accident doesnât happen.</h3>\r\n</div>', 'Slide 44 - THE ERROR CHAIN', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-44-the-error-chain', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:46:57', '2014-11-14 09:46:57', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=112', 43, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(113, 1, '2014-11-13 09:30:44', '2014-11-13 09:30:44', '', 'Slide 45 - Interactive Question', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-45-question', '', '', '2014-12-09 08:56:00', '2014-12-09 08:56:00', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=113', 44, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(114, 1, '2014-11-13 09:30:55', '2014-11-13 09:30:55', '', 'Slide 46 - Question', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-46-question', '', '', '2014-11-14 10:39:22', '2014-11-14 10:39:22', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=114', 45, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(115, 1, '2014-11-13 09:31:09', '2014-11-13 09:31:09', '<div id="slide_47">\r\n<h3>The organisation and social environment:</h3>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>Teamwork and team structure</li>\r\n<li>Supervision and Supportive management</li>\r\n<li>Communications</li>\r\n<li>Resources.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>', 'Slide 47 - EFFICIENCY OF THE ORGANISATION', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-47-efficiency-of-the-organisation', '', '', '2014-11-14 10:41:37', '2014-11-14 10:41:37', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=115', 46, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(116, 1, '2014-11-13 09:31:20', '2014-11-13 09:31:20', '<h1>What is needed to have Efficiency of the organisation?</h1>\r\n<h3>Please drag the correct triangles into the hexagon.</h3>', 'Slide 48 - Interactive Question', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-48-question', '', '', '2015-02-03 11:46:04', '2015-02-03 11:46:04', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=116', 47, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(117, 1, '2014-11-13 09:31:35', '2014-11-13 09:31:35', '[row]\r\n[column_4]\r\n<img class="size-full wp-image-203 aligncenter" src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_49.png" alt="slide_49" width="183" height="352" />\r\n[/column_4]\r\n[column_8]\r\n&nbsp;\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h1 style="text-align: center;">CATEGORIES OF HUMAN FACTORS\r\nTHAT ARE IMPORTANT TO\r\nAERONAUTICAL ENGINEERING STAFF</h1>\r\n[/column_8]\r\n[/row]', 'Slide 49 - CATEGORIES OF HUMAN FACTORS ', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-49-categories-of-human-factors', '', '', '2014-11-14 10:46:17', '2014-11-14 10:46:17', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=117', 48, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(118, 1, '2014-11-13 09:31:49', '2014-11-13 09:31:49', '<div class="safety_culture">\r\n<h3>The aircraft maintainer can expect to work in a variety of different environments:</h3>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>âlineâ (generally outside the hangar)</li>\r\n<li>âbaseâ (usually inside a hangar or workshop)</li>\r\n<li>In all types of weather and climatic conditions, day and night</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3>Physical environments have their own specific features or factors that may affect human performance: </h3>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>Noise</li>\r\n<li>Fumes</li>\r\n<li>Illumination</li>\r\n<li>Climate and temperature</li>\r\n<li>Motion and vibration</li>\r\n<li>Requirement to work in confined spaces and the general working environment.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>', 'Slide 50 - WORKING ENVIRONMENT', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-50-working-environment', '', '', '2014-11-14 10:49:17', '2014-11-14 10:49:17', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=118', 49, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(119, 1, '2014-11-13 09:33:11', '2014-11-13 09:33:11', 'INTERACTIVE QUESTION   What are the features or factors that may  affect  human performance: \r\nNoise\r\nFumes\r\nIllumination\r\nClimate and temperature\r\nMotion and vibration\r\nWell stocked spares\r\nHaving all the correct tooling and equipment\r\nINSERT FIVE CORRECT ANSWERS INTO FIVE PARTS OF A PYRAMID SHAPE\r\nREFERS to previous slide for go back to', 'Slide 51 - Interactive Question', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-51-question', '', '', '2015-02-10 15:26:02', '2015-02-10 15:26:02', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=119', 50, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(120, 1, '2014-11-13 09:33:30', '2014-11-13 09:33:30', '<h3>All aircraft maintainers are skilled individuals having undertaken considerable training. They work in a highly professional environment in BAE Systems Saudi Arabia and generally have considerable pride in their work and its contribution to air safety.</h3>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<img src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_52.png" alt="slide_52" width="679" height="335" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-206" />', 'Slide 52 - INDIVIDUAL RESPONSIBILITY', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-52-individual-responsibility', '', '', '2014-11-14 10:51:39', '2014-11-14 10:51:39', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=120', 51, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(121, 1, '2014-11-13 09:33:54', '2014-11-13 09:33:54', '<h3>Group responsibility has its advantages and disadvantages:</h3>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3>Advantages:</h3>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>Each group member should feel responsible for the output of that group, not just their own output as an individual, and ought to work towards ensuring that the whole âproductâ is safe </li>\r\n<li>This may involve cross-checking othersâ work (even when not strictly required), politely challenging others if you think that something is not quite right, etc.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3>Disadvantages:</h3>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>It can potentially act against safety, with responsibility being devolved to such an extent that no-one feels personally responsible for safety (referred to as diffusion of responsibility)</li>\r\n<li>Here, an individual, on his own, may take action but, once placed within a group situation, he may not act if none of the other group members do so, each member of the group or team assuming that âsomeone else will do itâ. </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', 'Slide 53 - GROUP OR TEAM RESPONSIBILITY', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-53-group-or-team-responsibility', '', '', '2014-11-14 10:53:32', '2014-11-14 10:53:32', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=121', 52, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(122, 1, '2014-11-13 09:34:07', '2014-11-13 09:34:07', '<div id="slide_54">\r\n<h3>This where situations evolve where a small group may act cohesively as a team, but rivalries may arise between this team and others:</h3>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n	<li>Between engineers and planners</li>\r\n	<li>Between shifts</li>\r\n	<li>Between teams at different sites</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3 class="blueish" style="text-align: center;">âThis may have implications in terms of responsibility, with teams failing to share responsibility between them.â</h3>\r\n</div>', 'Slide 54 - INTERGROUP CONFLICT', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-54-intergroup-conflict', '', '', '2014-11-14 10:58:34', '2014-11-14 10:58:34', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=122', 53, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(123, 1, '2014-11-13 09:34:19', '2014-11-13 09:34:19', '<h3>Due to the nature of aircraft maintenance, personnel can be regularly be asked to work a shift pattern. These can cause problems such as:</h3>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>Working âunsociable hoursâ, meaning that time available with friends, family will be disrupted</li>\r\n<li>Working when human performance is known to be poorer (i.e. between 4 a.m. and 6 a.m.)</li>\r\n<li>Cultural differences within Saudi Arabia</li>\r\n<li>Problems associated with general de-synchronisation and disturbance of the bodyâs various rhythms (principally sleeping patterns).</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Slide 55 - WORK PATTERNS', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-55-work-patterns', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:02:59', '2014-11-14 11:02:59', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=123', 54, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(124, 1, '2014-11-13 09:34:30', '2014-11-13 09:34:30', '', 'Slide 56 - Question', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-56-question', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:04:50', '2014-11-14 11:04:50', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=124', 55, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(125, 1, '2014-11-13 09:34:45', '2014-11-13 09:34:45', '<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li><i>Circa</i> = about    <i>Dies</i> = day</li>\r\n<li>Virtually all species have developed biological clocks with frequencies close to 24 hours</li>\r\n<li>The human works on a predominantly 25.3 hour cycle.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<img src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_57.png" alt="slide_57" width="1598" height="981" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-210" />', 'Slide 57 - CIRCADIAN RHYTHMS', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-57-circadian-rhythms', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:06:58', '2014-11-14 11:06:58', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=125', 56, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(126, 1, '2014-11-13 09:34:57', '2014-11-13 09:34:57', '', 'Slide 58 - Question', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-58-question', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:09:38', '2014-11-14 11:09:38', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=126', 57, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(127, 1, '2014-11-13 09:35:12', '2014-11-13 09:35:12', '<img src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_59.png" alt="slide_59" width="572" height="382" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-213" />', 'Slide 59 - COMMUNICATION', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-59-communication', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:14:31', '2014-11-14 11:14:31', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=127', 58, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(128, 1, '2014-11-13 09:35:27', '2014-11-13 09:35:27', '\r\n<a class="fancybox-media fancybox-youtube" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DVwHCGAr_OE">\r\n<img class="alignright size-full wp-image-226" width="228" height="171" alt="slide_73-b" src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_73-b.png">\r\n</a>\r\n<a href="http://youtu.be/N_tONWXYviM?hd=1&fs=1&autoplay=1">text or thumbnail</a>', 'Slide 60 - COMMUNICATION CAN GO WRONG', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-60-communication-can-go-wrong', '', '', '2015-02-04 12:02:43', '2015-02-04 12:02:43', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=128', 59, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(129, 1, '2014-11-13 09:36:48', '2014-11-13 09:36:48', '<h3>Why is good communication important?</h3>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>Spoken and written communication can be critical in maintaining safety</li>\r\n<li>This can include general communications in the form of safety information</li>\r\n<li>Communications between team members or between different teams during operations or maintenance work</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', 'Slide 61 - COMMUNICATION', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-61-communication', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:16:03', '2014-11-14 11:16:03', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=129', 60, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(130, 1, '2014-11-13 09:37:01', '2014-11-13 09:37:01', '<h3>Generally speaking, verbal and written communication are purposeful. For a spoken or written message to be understood, the sender has to make sure that the receiver:</h3>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>Is using the same channel of communication</li>\r\n<li>Recognises and understands his language</li>\r\n<li>Is able to make sense of the messageâs meaning</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3>The channel of communication is the medium used to convey the message: </h3>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>For spoken communication, this might be face-to-face, or via the telephone</li>\r\n<li>Written messages might be notes, memos, documents or e-mails</li>\r\n<li>Shift handovers.</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Slide 62 - VERBAL AND WRITTEN COMMUNICATION', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-62-verbal-and-written-communication', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:17:57', '2014-11-14 11:17:57', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=130', 61, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(131, 1, '2014-11-13 09:37:15', '2014-11-13 09:37:15', '', 'Slide 63 - Question', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-63-question', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:25:50', '2014-11-14 11:25:50', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=131', 62, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(132, 1, '2014-11-13 09:37:27', '2014-11-13 09:37:27', '[row]\r\n[column_6]\r\n<h3>Methods used for Communication</h3>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>Hand signals</li>\r\n<li>Radios</li>\r\n<li>Mobile phones.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/column_6]\r\n[column_6]\r\n<img src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_64.png" alt="slide_64" width="355" height="301" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-216" />\r\n[/column_6]\r\n[/row]', 'Slide 64 - COMMUNICATION', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-64-communication', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:27:46', '2014-11-14 11:27:46', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=132', 63, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(133, 1, '2014-11-13 09:37:40', '2014-11-13 09:37:40', '<img src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_65.png" alt="slide_65" width="1288" height="864" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-217" />', 'Slide 65 - COMMUNICATION IS A THREE WAY PROCESS', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-65-communication-is-a-three-way-process', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:28:25', '2014-11-14 11:28:25', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=133', 64, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(134, 1, '2014-11-13 09:37:54', '2014-11-13 09:37:54', '<h3>For teams to function cohesively and productively, team members need to have or build up certain interpersonal and social skills. </h3>\r\n[row]\r\n[column_6]\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3>These include:</h3>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>Communication</li>\r\n<li>Cooperation</li>\r\n<li>Co-ordination </li>\r\n<li>Mutual support.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/column_6]\r\n[column_6]\r\n<img src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_66.png" alt="slide_66" width="529" height="298" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-218" />\r\n[/column_6]\r\n[/row]', 'Slide 66 - IMPORTANT ELEMENTS OF TEAM WORKING', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-66-important-elements-of-team-working', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:31:01', '2014-11-14 11:31:01', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=134', 65, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(135, 1, '2014-11-13 09:38:11', '2014-11-13 09:38:11', 'Interactive Question:\r\nWhat makes Team work more effective?\r\nCommunication\r\nCooperation\r\nCo-ordination\r\nMutual support.\r\nLack of respect \r\nPoor communication\r\nLack of cooperation\r\nNo co-ordination \r\nForm as a interactive question around the four correct answers in red\r\nREFERS to previous slide for go back to', 'Slide 67 - Interactive Question', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-67-question', '', '', '2015-02-13 04:48:09', '2015-02-13 04:48:09', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=135', 66, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(136, 1, '2014-11-13 09:38:24', '2014-11-13 09:38:24', '<h3>Fitness and health can have a significant affect (both physical and cognitive). </h3>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3>Many conditions can impact on the health and fitness of an maintainer:</h3>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>Minor and major physical illness (such as colds, âFlu, to HIV and Malaria.)</li>\r\n<li>Mental illness (such as depression, etc.)</li>\r\n<li>Minor and major injuries (such as a sprained wrist to broken arms)</li>\r\n<li>On-going deterioration in physical condition, possibly associated with the ageing process (such as hearing loss, visual defects, obesity, heart problems, etc.)</li>\r\n<li>Effects of toxins and other foreign substances (such as carbon monoxide poisoning, over-counter medications, illicit drugs, etc.)</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Slide 68 - EMPLOYEE HEALTH AND SOCIAL HABITS', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-68-employee-health-and-social-habits', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:32:52', '2014-11-14 11:32:52', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=136', 67, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(137, 1, '2014-11-13 09:38:37', '2014-11-13 09:38:37', '<h3>Aircraft maintainers can take common sense steps to maintain their fitness and health.  In your groups, discuss what these include:</h3>\r\n[row]\r\n[column_6]\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>Eating regular meals and a well-balanced diet</li>\r\n<li>Taking regular exercise (exercise sufficient to double the resting pulse rate for 20 minutes, three times a week is often recommended)</li>\r\n<li>Using Personal Protective Equipment (PPE)</li>\r\n<li>Using barrier creams</li>\r\n<li>Sun precaution</li>\r\n<li>Taking care of each other</li>\r\n<li>Stopping smoking.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/column_6]\r\n[column_6]\r\n<img src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_69.png" alt="slide_69" width="333" height="293" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-222" />\r\n[/column_6]\r\n[/row]', 'Slide 69 - EMPLOYEE HEALTH AND SOCIAL HABITS', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-69-employee-health-and-social-habits', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:35:21', '2014-11-14 11:35:21', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=137', 68, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(138, 1, '2014-11-13 09:38:47', '2014-11-13 09:38:47', 'QUESTION  INTERACTIVE  SELECT with a marker in the box \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nDifferent stressors affect different people to varying extents. Stressors may be:\r\nNot working  shift patterns\r\nGetting on with  with managers or colleagues\r\nPhysical - such as heat, cold, noise, vibration, presence of something damaging to health (e.g. carbon monoxide)\r\nGood health\r\nBeing able to take regular breaks\r\nPsychological - such as emotional upset (e.g. due to bereavements, domestic problems, etc.) \r\nWorries about real or imagined problems (e.g. due to financial problems, ill health, etc.)\r\nReactive - such as events occurring in everyday life (e.g. working under time pressure, encountering unexpected situations, etc.).\r\nNO time pressure\r\nEnvironment â correctly controlled\r\n\r\n', 'Slide 70 - Interactive Question', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-70-question', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:36:10', '2014-11-14 11:36:10', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=138', 69, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(139, 1, '2014-11-13 09:40:23', '2014-11-13 09:40:23', '<h3>Different stressors affect different people to varying extents. Stressors may be:</h3>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>Physical - such as heat, cold, noise, vibration, presence of something damaging to health (e.g. carbon monoxide)</li>\r\n<li>Psychological - such as emotional upset (e.g. due to bereavements, domestic problems, etc.) </li>\r\n<li>Worries about real or imagined problems (e.g. due to financial problems, ill health, etc.)</li>\r\n<li>Reactive - such as events occurring in everyday life (e.g. working under time pressure, encountering unexpected situations, etc.).</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Slide 71 - CAUSES AND SYMPTOMS OF STRESS', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-71-causes-and-symptoms-of-stress', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:37:13', '2014-11-14 11:37:13', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=139', 70, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(140, 1, '2014-11-13 09:40:35', '2014-11-13 09:40:35', '<h3>When aircraft maintainers go to work, they cannot leave stresses associated with home behind. Domestic stress typically results from major life changes at home, such as:</h3>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n	<li>Marriage</li>\r\n	<li>Birth of a child</li>\r\n	<li>A son or daughter leaving home</li>\r\n	<li>Bereavement of a close family member or friend</li>\r\n	<li>Divorce</li>\r\n	<li>Family commitments</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3 class="blueish" style="text-align: center;">âInability to concentrate fully may impact on the maintainerâs task performance and ability to pay due attention to safety.â</h3>', 'Slide 72 - DOMESTIC STRESS', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-72-domestic-stress', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:39:12', '2014-11-14 11:39:12', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=140', 71, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(141, 1, '2014-11-13 09:40:47', '2014-11-13 09:40:47', '<h3>In your groups please list 5 stressors that could lead to stress at work:</h3>\r\n[row]\r\n[column_6]\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>Too much work</li>\r\n<li>Changing shift patterns</li>\r\n<li>Personal problems, family problems</li>\r\n<li>Conflict with managers or colleagues</li>\r\n<li>Peer pressure</li>\r\n<li>Fatigue</li>\r\n<li>Time pressure</li>\r\n<li>Environment â too hot too cold</li>\r\n<li>Noise</li>\r\n<li>Poor health</li>\r\n<li>Not taking regular breaks</li>\r\n<li>Lack of rest periods.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/column_6]\r\n[column_6]\r\n<img src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_73-a.png" alt="slide_73-a" width="254" height="182" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-225" />\r\n<img src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_73-b.png" alt="slide_73-b" width="228" height="171" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-226" />\r\n[/column_6]\r\n[/row]\r\n', 'Slide 73 - GROUP TASK', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-73-group-task', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:41:54', '2014-11-14 11:41:54', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=141', 72, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(142, 1, '2014-11-13 09:40:59', '2014-11-13 09:40:59', '<h3>As already discussed one of the potential stressors in maintenance is time pressure:</h3>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3>Actual</h3>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>Pressure where clearly specified deadlines are imposed by an external source (e.g. management or supervisors) and passed on to the maintainers</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Perceived </h3>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>Where maintainers feel that there are time pressures when carrying out tasks, even when no definitive deadlines have been set in stone</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Self-imposed</h3>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>Engineers set themselves deadlines to complete work (e.g. completing a task before a break or before the end of a shift)</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Slide 74 - TIME PRESSURE AND DEADLINES', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-74-time-pressure-and-deadlines', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:43:47', '2014-11-14 11:43:47', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=142', 73, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(143, 1, '2014-11-13 09:41:12', '2014-11-13 09:41:12', '<h3>As with stress, some time pressure is stimulating and may actually improve task performance:</h3>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n	<li>However, it is almost certainly true that excessive time pressure (either actual or perceived, external or self-imposed), is likely to mean that due care and attention when carrying out tasks diminishes and more errors will be made</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3 class="blueish" style="text-align: center;">âUltimately, these errors can lead to aircraft incidents and accidentsâ</h3>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<img src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_75.png" alt="slide_75" width="319" height="214" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-229" />', 'Slide 75 - TIME PRESSURE AND DEADLINES', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-75-time-pressure-and-deadlines', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:46:00', '2014-11-14 11:46:00', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=143', 74, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(144, 1, '2014-11-13 09:41:25', '2014-11-13 09:41:25', '<h3>If an overload of the working situation is developing, methods to help relieve this include:</h3>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n	<li>Seeking a simpler method of carrying out the work (that is just as effective and still legitimate)</li>\r\n	<li>Delegating certain activities to others to avoid an individual maintainer becoming overloaded</li>\r\n	<li>Securing further time in order to carry out the work safely</li>\r\n	<li>Postponing, delaying tasks / deadlines and refusing additional work</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3 class="blueish" style="text-align: center;">âMuch of this can be done by careful forward planning of tasks, manpower, spares, tools and ensuring staff are fully trained.â</h3>', 'Slide 76 - WORKLOAD MANAGEMENT', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-76-workload-management', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:47:20', '2014-11-14 11:47:20', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=144', 75, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(145, 1, '2014-11-13 09:41:37', '2014-11-13 09:41:37', '<h3>Here are some of the thinks that can causes individual fatigue:</h3>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n[row]\r\n[column_6]\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>Excessive hours of work</li>\r\n<li>Insufficient out of hours rest/sleep</li>\r\n<li>Dehydration</li>\r\n<li>Organisational</li>\r\n<li>Poor planning of work</li>\r\n<li>Insufficient personnel</li>\r\n<li>Poor shift pattern</li>\r\n<li>Temperature, humidity, noise.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/column_6]\r\n[column_6]\r\n<img src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_77.png" alt="slide_77" width="255" height="182" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-230" />\r\n[/column_6]\r\n[/row]', 'Slide 77 - FATIGUE', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-77-fatigue', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:50:43', '2014-11-14 11:50:43', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=145', 76, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(146, 1, '2014-11-13 09:41:47', '2014-11-13 09:41:47', 'INTERACTIVE QUESTION   Select four causes  of FATIGUE\r\nMark the correct options from the listing\r\n\r\nExcessive hours of work\r\nOnly working short hours per day\r\nMental and physically\r\nInsufficient out of hours rest/sleep\r\nBeing  correctly hydrated\r\nOrganisational\r\nPoor planning of work\r\nWell planned work\r\nInsufficient personnel\r\nGood shift pattern\r\nPoor shift pattern\r\nTemperature, humidity, noise.\r\nREFERS to previous slide for go back to\r\n', 'Slide 78 - Interactive Question', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-78-question', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:51:00', '2014-11-14 11:51:00', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=146', 77, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(147, 1, '2014-11-13 09:42:02', '2014-11-13 09:42:02', '<h3>Humans can work within quite a wide range of temperatures and climatic conditions, but performance is adversely affected at extremes of these:</h3>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<img src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_79.png" alt="slide_79" width="645" height="352" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-232" />', 'Slide 79 - TEMPERATURE AND CLIMATE', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-79-temperature-and-climate', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:51:44', '2014-11-14 11:51:44', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=147', 78, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(148, 1, '2014-11-13 09:42:14', '2014-11-13 09:42:14', '<h3>An incident occurred where a set of adjustable staging was used during day-shift and remained in place over the night period. The staging failed to maintain the selected height and position during the night and at start of day shift, next day the staging was found to be resting against the aircraft. This resulted in minor damage to the aircraft rear fuselage and required a seal to be replaced on the aircraft.</h3>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>YOU HAVE NOW ARRIVED AT THE AIRCRAFT?<img class="alignright size-full wp-image-233" src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_80.png" alt="slide_80" width="185" height="124" /></h2>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n	<li>In groups discuss the incident that happened</li>\r\n	<li>What would be the next step</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Slide 80 - CASE STUDY 1', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-80-case-study-1', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:53:15', '2014-11-14 11:53:15', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=148', 79, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(149, 1, '2014-11-13 09:42:26', '2014-11-13 09:42:26', '<h1>Raise a report of the incident</h1>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n	<li>This resulted in minor damage to the aircraft rear fuselage and required a seal to be replaced on the aircraft.</li>\r\n	<li>Staging removed from service and quarantined due to concerns over its failure to maintain the selected height.</li>\r\n	<li>Proposed and looked at the introduction of a secondary fail safe features for the staging and then assess if fit for purpose.</li>\r\n	<li>Following investigations and the SRG (Safety Review Group) item found not fit for purpose and withdrawn from use.</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Slide 81 - CASE STUDY 1 RESULTS', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-81-case-study-1-results', '', '', '2014-12-01 16:49:02', '2014-12-01 16:49:02', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=149', 80, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(150, 1, '2014-11-13 09:42:40', '2014-11-13 09:42:40', '<h3>During start up Crew Chief observed an oil leak from the engine bay area. The pilot was directed to shut down and the mission was aborted. A propulsion technician inspected the aircraft and identified the Oil filler cap dipstick assembly was not properly secured. A Flight Line Mechanic had fitted the oil filler dipstick on the aircraft.</h3>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>YOU HAVE NOW ARRIVED AT THE AIRCRAFT<img class="alignright size-full wp-image-234" src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_82.png" alt="slide_82" width="225" height="170" /></h2>\r\n<ul class="big_ul">\r\n	<li>In your groups discuss this incident and how this could be prevented from happening again.</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Slide 82 - CASE STUDY 2', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-82-case-study-2', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:55:25', '2014-11-14 11:55:25', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=150', 81, 'aviation-questions', '', 0),
(151, 1, '2014-11-13 09:42:51', '2014-11-13 09:42:51', '<ul class="big_ul">\r\n<li>Report raised from incident.</li>\r\n<li>Oil filler cap dipstick assembly identified item serviceable.</li>\r\n<li>FLM not fully familiar with the aircraft system as on a previous model.</li>\r\n<li>Oil filler assembly refitted with new âOâ ring and oil level  replenished and area cleaned of residue.</li>\r\n<li>Training package brought in to show correct method of locking  the assembly with a Safety Information Leaflet produced. </li>\r\n<li>Aircraft returned to serviceable status.</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Slide 83 - CASE STUDY 2 RESULTS', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'slide-83-case-study-2-results', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:56:26', '2014-11-14 11:56:26', '', 0, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/?post_type=aviation-questions&#038;p=151', 82, 'aviation-questions', '', 0);
