(177, 1, '2014-11-14 08:24:32', '2014-11-14 08:24:32', '<div id="slide_18">\n<h1 style="text-align: center;">Journey to the bottom of the Iceberg?</h1>\n<h3 class="red" style="text-align: center;">1 fatal accident</h3>\n<h3 style="text-align: center;">10 non-fatal accidents</h3>\n<h3 style="text-align: center;">30 reportable incidents</h3>\n<h4 style="text-align: center;">Incidents are rehearsals for accidents - we can learn from them if our culture allows us to</h4>\n<h2 style="text-align: center;">000âs unsafe acts</h2>\n<h5>Source: Heinrich</h5>\n</div>', 'Slide 20 - ICEBERG ', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '88-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 08:24:32', '2014-11-14 08:24:32', '', 88, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/88-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(178, 1, '2014-11-14 08:45:53', '2014-11-14 08:45:53', '<ul class="big_ul">\n<li>An incorrect fitting of a part that can be fitted in a number of different ways\n<i><span class="reddish">- Why report :</span> <span class="blueish">amend design to âMurphy Proofâ</span></i>\n</li>\n<li>Inaccurate, incomplete or confusing technical instructions\n<i><span class="reddish">- - Why report :</span> amend the instructions to prevent others getting it wrong</span></i>\n</li>\n<li>Lack of spares, tools & equipment (only after giving management the opportunity to resolve)\n- Why report :</span> to ensure resources are provided</span></i>\n</li>\n<li>An honest mistake youâve made whilst undertaking manufacturing activities\n- Why report :</span> so others can learn from your mistake</span></i>\n</li>\n</ul>', 'Slide 22 - TYPES OF ISSUES TO REPORT', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '90-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 08:45:53', '2014-11-14 08:45:53', '', 90, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/90-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(179, 1, '2014-11-14 08:47:55', '2014-11-14 08:47:55', '<div class="safety_culture">\n<ul class="big_ul">\n<li>The successful implementation of an Error Management System (EMS) will enable managers to maximise their ability to identify, mitigate and manage risks by involving all staff in the reporting and subsequent analysis of potential hazards, system failures and human errors in order to minimise the potential for recurrence. </li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3 class="blueish">âTHE LIFEBLOOD OF ANY ERROR MANAGEMENT SYSTEM \nIS REPORTINGâ\n</div>', 'Slide 23 - ERROR MANAGEMENT SYSTEM ', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '91-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 08:47:55', '2014-11-14 08:47:55', '', 91, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/91-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(180, 1, '2014-11-14 08:53:00', '2014-11-14 08:53:00', '', 'slide_24', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', 'slide_24', '', '', '2014-11-14 08:53:00', '2014-11-14 08:53:00', '', 92, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_24.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(181, 1, '2014-11-14 08:55:08', '2014-11-14 08:55:08', '<div class="safety_culture">\n<h3>The M&CA EMS provides a mechanism to report, investigate and prevent:</h3>\n<ul class="big_ul">\n<li>Maintenance errors</li>\n<li>Procedures that are ambiguous or inaccurate</li>\n<li>Mismatches between required and actual practices and</li>\n<li>Any other condition which could lead to an error (if left unresolved).</li>\n</ul>\n</div>', 'Slide 25 - ERROR MANAGEMENT SYSTEM', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '93-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 08:55:08', '2014-11-14 08:55:08', '', 93, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/93-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(182, 1, '2014-11-14 08:59:01', '2014-11-14 08:59:01', '<div class="safety_culture">\n<h3>Error? </h3>\n<ul class="big_ul">\n<li>Where a person should have done other than what they did</li>\n<li><b>Unintentional</b></li>\n</ul>\nMaintenance Error?\nThe maintenance system (which includes people) fails to perform in the manner expected\n</div>', 'Slide 27 - TYPES OF ERRORS', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '95-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 08:59:01', '2014-11-14 08:59:01', '', 95, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/95-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(183, 1, '2014-11-14 09:05:23', '2014-11-14 09:05:23', '', 'slide_29-a', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', 'slide_29-a', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:05:23', '2014-11-14 09:05:23', '', 97, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_29-a.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(184, 1, '2014-11-14 09:07:18', '2014-11-14 09:07:18', '[row]\n[column_8]\n<h3>Active failures: </h3>\n<ul class="big_ul">\nErrors having an immediate impact\n[/column_8]\n[column_4]\n<img src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_29-a.png" alt="slide_29-a" width="291" height="202" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-183" />\n[/column_4]\n[/row]\n\n[row]\n[column_8]\n<h3>Latent failures: </h3>\n<ul class="big_ul">\n<li>Errors that lay dormant for a long time \nTypically only becoming apparent when they combine with other failures and local triggering events \nIt is then that an accident occurs, exampleâ¦\n[/column_8]\n[column_4]\n<img src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_29-b.png" alt="slide_29-b" width="293" height="204" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-185" />\n[/column_4]\n[/row]', 'Slide 29 - TWO TYPES OF ERRORS', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '97-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:07:18', '2014-11-14 09:07:18', '', 97, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/97-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(185, 1, '2014-11-14 09:06:04', '2014-11-14 09:06:04', '', 'slide_29-b', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', 'slide_29-b', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:06:04', '2014-11-14 09:06:04', '', 97, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_29-b.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(186, 1, '2014-11-14 09:10:59', '2014-11-14 09:10:59', '<div class="safety_culture">\n<h3>VIOLATION</h3>\n<ul class="big_ul">\n<li>What caused this and how does it differ from ERROR</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>INTENTIONAL</h3>\nA human action or behaviour\n\nTHREE TYPES:\nOrganisational Gain- A maintainer engages in a practice that is condoned by management , that bends the rules.\nPersonal Gain â A maintainer strays from the accepted procedures to save time that bends the rules.\nReckless â A maintainer wilfully breaks standing rules disregarding the consequences.\n</div>', 'Slide 31 - WHAT ELSE MIGHT WE HAVE IF NOT AN ERROR', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '99-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:10:59', '2014-11-14 09:10:59', '', 99, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/99-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(187, 1, '2014-11-14 09:17:19', '2014-11-14 09:17:19', '<div class="safety_culture">\n<ul class="big_ul">\n<li>BAE Systems Saudi Arabia has the FAiR tool provided by Baines Simmons to look at what has happened post investigations.</li>\n<li>Lets take a brief look at this tool ......</li>\n</ul>\n</div>', 'Slide 34 - TOOLS AVAILABLE TO LOOK AT INCIDENTS ', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '102-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:17:19', '2014-11-14 09:17:19', '', 102, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/102-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(188, 1, '2014-11-14 09:17:49', '2014-11-14 09:17:49', '', 'slide_35', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', 'slide_35', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:17:49', '2014-11-14 09:17:49', '', 103, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_35.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
