(190, 1, '2014-11-14 09:21:00', '2014-11-14 09:21:00', '[row]\n[column_4]\n', 'Slide 37 - IMPORTANCE OF HUMAN FACTORS', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '105-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:21:00', '2014-11-14 09:21:00', '', 105, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/105-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(191, 1, '2014-11-14 09:21:05', '2014-11-14 09:21:05', '', 'slide_37', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', 'slide_37', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:21:05', '2014-11-14 09:21:05', '', 105, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_37.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(192, 1, '2014-11-14 09:24:56', '2014-11-14 09:24:56', '<div class="safety_culture">\n<h3>Applying Human Factors to the workplace can:</h3>\n<ul class="big_ul">\n<li>Reduce the potential for accidents </li>\n<li>Reduce the potential for injury and ill health</li>\n<li>Improve performance and productivity</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>SO WHAT DO YOU THINK ABOUT THE ABOVE?</h2>\n\nâTHESE ARE ONLY EFFECTIVE IF WE REPORT THE PROBLEMSâ\n\n\n', 'Slide 38 - BENEFITS OF HUMAN FACTORS', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '106-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:24:56', '2014-11-14 09:24:56', '', 106, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/106-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(193, 1, '2014-11-14 09:28:12', '2014-11-14 09:28:12', '<h2>We work in an environment that produces error:</h2>\n&nbsp;\n<ul class="big_ul">\n<li>We frequently remove and replace many parts</li>\n<li>Sometimes with less than adequate tooling, equipment, parts, knowledge or time</li>\n<li>People who write the manuals, work instructions & procedures hardly ever do the job for real</li>\n<li>People who start on a job are not necessarily the ones to finish it</li>\n<li>Our system requires many people to do their job to enable the last person touching the aircraft to do theirs...</li>\n</ul>\n&n\n', 'Slide 40 - HUMAN FACTORS IN THE ENGINEERING WORKPLACE', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '108-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:28:12', '2014-11-14 09:28:12', '', 108, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/108-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(194, 1, '2014-11-14 09:28:22', '2014-11-14 09:28:22', '', 'slide_40', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', 'slide_40', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:28:22', '2014-11-14 09:28:22', '', 108, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_40.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(195, 1, '2014-11-14 09:37:10', '2014-11-14 09:37:10', '<h3>Likely contributing factors:</h3>\n<ul class="big_ul">\n<li>Fails to use approved data or company procedures</li>\n<li>Staff shortages</li>\n<li>Time pressures</li>\n<li>Errors occur at night</li>\n<li>Shift & task handovers</li>\n<li>Communication & Reporting breakdown</li>\n<li>Supervisors carrying out long hands-on tasks</li>\n<âCan-doâ attitude\n\nInterruptions\n\nInadequate pre-planning, equipment or spares.', 'Slide 41 - HUMAN FACTORS AFFECTS ON SAFETY ', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '109-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:37:10', '2014-11-14 09:37:10', '', 109, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/109-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(196, 1, '2014-11-14 09:38:00', '2014-11-14 09:38:00', '', 'slide_41', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', 'slide_41', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:38:00', '2014-11-14 09:38:00', '', 109, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_41.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(197, 1, '2014-11-14 09:39:56', '2014-11-14 09:39:56', '<h4>Human Factors is also concerned with the âfitâ between people and their work. It puts people first, taking account of their capabilities and limitations. Human Factors aims to make sure that tasks, equipment, information and the environment fit each worker</h4>\n\n<h4><b>The job / task being done:</b></h4>\n<ul class="big_ul">\n<liThe demands on the worker (activities, workload, work pacing, shift work and fatigue)\nThe equipment used (its design in terms of size, shape, controls, displays, and how appropriate it is for the task)\nThe information used (how it is presented, accessed, and changed)\nThe physical environment (temperature, humidity, lighting, noise and vibration).', 'Slide 42 - HUMAN FACTORS', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '110-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:39:56', '2014-11-14 09:39:56', '', 110, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/110-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(198, 1, '2014-11-14 09:42:10', '2014-11-14 09:42:10', '', 'slide_43', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', 'slide_43', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:42:10', '2014-11-14 09:42:10', '', 111, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_43.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(199, 1, '2014-11-14 09:43:56', '2014-11-14 09:43:56', '', 'slide_44', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', 'slide_44', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:43:56', '2014-11-14 09:43:56', '', 112, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_44.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(200, 1, '2014-11-14 09:46:49', '2014-11-14 09:46:49', '<div id="slide_44">\n<div id="slide_44_in">\n<h3>Chain of events:</h3>\n<ul class="big_ul">\n<li>Multiple contributing causes that can lead to an accident</li>\n<li>Rarely does an accident havea single cause\n</div>\n<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-199" src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_44.png" alt="slide_44" width="1847" height="1160" />\n<h3 class="blueish" style="text-align: center;">If we can break just one link in the chain, the accident doesnât happen.</h3>\n</div>', 'Slide 44 - THE ERROR CHAIN', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '112-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 09:46:49', '2014-11-14 09:46:49', '', 112, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/112-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(201, 1, '2014-11-14 10:40:45', '2014-11-14 10:40:45', '', 'slide_47', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', 'slide_47', '', '', '2014-11-14 10:40:45', '2014-11-14 10:40:45', '', 115, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_47.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(202, 1, '2014-11-14 10:40:57', '2014-11-14 10:40:57', '<h3>The organisation and social environment:</h3>\n<ul class="big_ul">\n<li>Teamwork and team structure</li>\n<li>Supervision and Supportive management</li>\n<li>Communications</li>\n<li>Resources.</li>\n</ul>\n', 'Slide 47 - EFFICIENCY OF THE ORGANISATION', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '115-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 10:40:57', '2014-11-14 10:40:57', '', 115, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/115-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(203, 1, '2014-11-14 10:44:23', '2014-11-14 10:44:23', '', 'slide_49', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', 'slide_49', '', '', '2014-11-14 10:44:23', '2014-11-14 10:44:23', '', 117, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_49.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(204, 1, '2014-11-14 10:45:02', '2014-11-14 10:45:02', '[row]\n[column_4]\n<img src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_49.png" alt="slide_49" width="183" height="352" class="alignright size-full wp-image-203" />\n[/column_4]\n[column_8]\n<h1>CATEGORIES OF HUMAN FACTORS \nTHAT ARE IMPORTANT TO \nAERONAUTICAL ENGINEERING STAFF</h1>\n[/column_8]\n[/row]', 'Slide 49 - CATEGORIES OF HUMAN FACTORS ', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '117-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 10:45:02', '2014-11-14 10:45:02', '', 117, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/117-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(205, 1, '2014-11-14 10:48:12', '2014-11-14 10:48:12', '<div class="safety_culture">\n<h3>The aircraft maintainer can expect to work in a variety of different environments:</h3>\n<ul class="big_ul">\n<li>âlineâ (generally outside the hangar)</li>\n<li>âbaseâ (usually inside a hangar or workshop)</li>\n<li>In all types of weather and climatic conditions, day and night</l\n</ul>\n\n\n</div>', 'Slide 50 - WORKING ENVIRONMENT', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '118-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 10:48:12', '2014-11-14 10:48:12', '', 118, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/118-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(206, 1, '2014-11-14 10:50:51', '2014-11-14 10:50:51', '', 'slide_52', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', 'slide_52', '', '', '2014-11-14 10:50:51', '2014-11-14 10:50:51', '', 120, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_52.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(207, 1, '2014-11-14 10:53:15', '2014-11-14 10:53:15', '<h3>Group responsibility has its advantages and disadvantages:</h3>\n&nbsp;\n<h3>Advantages:</h3>\n<ul class="big_ul">\n<li>Each group member should feel responsible for the output of that group, not just their own output as an individual, and ought to work towards ensuring that the whole âproductâ is safe </li>\n<li>This may involve cross-checking othersâ work (even when not strictly required), politely challenging others if you think that something is not quite right, etc.</li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n<h3>Disadvantages:</h3>\n<ul class="big_ul">\n<li>It can potentially act against safety, with responsibility being devolved to such an extent that no-one feels personally responsible for safety (referred to as diffusion of responsibility)\nHere, an individual, on his own, may take action but, once placed within a group situation, he may not act if none of the other group members do so, each member of the group or team assuming that âsomeone else will do itâ. \n', 'Slide 53 - GROUP OR TEAM RESPONSIBILITY', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '121-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 10:53:15', '2014-11-14 10:53:15', '', 121, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/121-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(208, 1, '2014-11-14 10:56:55', '2014-11-14 10:56:55', '<div id="slide_54"<h3>This where situations evolve where a small group may act cohesively as a team, but rivalries may arise between this team and others:</h3>\n<ul class="big_ul">\n<li>Between engineers and planners </li>\n<li>Between shifts</li>\n<li>Between teams at different sites</li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n<h3 class="blueish">âThis may have implications in terms of responsibility, with teams failing to share responsibility between them.â</h3>', 'Slide 54 - INTERGROUP CONFLICT', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '122-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 10:56:55', '2014-11-14 10:56:55', '', 122, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/122-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(209, 1, '2014-11-14 11:02:00', '2014-11-14 11:02:00', '<h3>Due to the nature of aircraft maintenance, personnel can be regularly be asked to work a shift pattern. These can cause problems such as:</h3>\n<ul\nWorking âunsociable hoursâ, meaning that time available with friends, family will be disrupted\n\nWorking when human performance is known to be poorer (i.e. between 4 a.m. and 6 a.m.)\n\nCultural differences within Saudi Arabia\n\nProblems associated with general de-synchronisation and disturbance of the bodyâs various rhythms (principally sleeping patterns).', 'Slide 55 - WORK PATTERNS', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '123-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:02:00', '2014-11-14 11:02:00', '', 123, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/123-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(210, 1, '2014-11-14 11:05:50', '2014-11-14 11:05:50', '', 'slide_57', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', 'slide_57', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:05:50', '2014-11-14 11:05:50', '', 125, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_57.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(211, 1, '2014-11-14 11:06:33', '2014-11-14 11:06:33', '<ul class="big_ul">\n<li><i>Circa = about    Dies = day</li>\n<li>Virtually all species have developed biological clocks with frequencies close to 24 hours</li>\n<li>The human works on a predominantly 25.3 hour cycle.</li>\n</ul>\n<img src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_57.png" alt="slide_57" width="1598" height="981" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-210" />', 'Slide 57 - CIRCADIAN RHYTHMS', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '125-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:06:33', '2014-11-14 11:06:33', '', 125, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/125-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(213, 1, '2014-11-14 11:14:22', '2014-11-14 11:14:22', '', 'slide_59', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', 'slide_59', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:14:22', '2014-11-14 11:14:22', '', 127, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_59.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(214, 1, '2014-11-14 11:17:36', '2014-11-14 11:17:36', '<h3>Generally speaking, verbal and written communication are purposeful. For a spoken or written message to be understood, the sender has to make sure that the receiver:</h3>\n<ul class="big_ul">\n<li>Is using the same channel of communication</li>\n<li>Recognises and understands his language</li>\n<li>Is able to make sense of the messageâs meaning</li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n<h3>The channel of communication is the medium used to convey the message: </h3>\n<ul class="big_ul">\n<li>For spoken communication, this might be face-to-face, or via the telephone\nWritten messages might be notes, memos, documents or           e-mails\nShift handovers.', 'Slide 62 - VERBAL AND WRITTEN COMMUNICATION', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '130-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:17:36', '2014-11-14 11:17:36', '', 130, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/130-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(215, 1, '2014-11-14 11:27:20', '2014-11-14 11:27:20', '[row]\n[column_6]\n<h3>Methods used for Communication</h3>\n<ul class="big_ul">\n<li>Hand signals</li>\n<li>Radios</li>\n<li>Mobile phones.</li>\n</ul>\n[/column_6]', 'Slide 64 - COMMUNICATION', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '132-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:27:20', '2014-11-14 11:27:20', '', 132, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/132-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(216, 1, '2014-11-14 11:27:31', '2014-11-14 11:27:31', '', 'slide_64', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', 'slide_64', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:27:31', '2014-11-14 11:27:31', '', 132, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_64.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(217, 1, '2014-11-14 11:28:18', '2014-11-14 11:28:18', '', 'slide_65', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', 'slide_65', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:28:18', '2014-11-14 11:28:18', '', 133, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_65.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(218, 1, '2014-11-14 11:29:17', '2014-11-14 11:29:17', '', 'slide_66', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', 'slide_66', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:29:17', '2014-11-14 11:29:17', '', 134, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_66.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(219, 1, '2014-11-14 11:29:51', '2014-11-14 11:29:51', '[row]\n[column_6]\n<h3>For teams to function cohesively and productively, team members need to have or build up certain interpersonal and social skills. </h3>\n<ul class="big_ul">\n\nCommunication\n\nCooperation\n\nCo-ordination \n\nMutual support.\n[/column_6]\n[column_6]\n<img src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_66.png" alt="slide_66" width="529" height="298" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-218" />\n[/column_6]\n[/row]', 'Slide 66 - IMPORTANT ELEMENTS OF TEAM WORKING', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '134-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:29:51', '2014-11-14 11:29:51', '', 134, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/134-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(220, 1, '2014-11-14 11:32:51', '2014-11-14 11:32:51', '<h3>Fitness and health can have a significant affect (both physical and cognitive). </h3>\n&nbsp;\n<h3>Many conditions can impact on the health and fitness of an maintainer:</h3>\n<ul class="big_ul">\n<li>Minor and major physical illness (such as colds, âFlu, to HIV and Malaria.)</li>\n<li>Mental illness (such as depression, etc.)</li>\n<li>Minor and major injuries (such as a sprained wrist to broken arms)</li>\n<li>On-going deterioration in physical condition, possibly associated with the ageing process (such as hearing loss, visual defects, obesity, heart problems, etc.)</li>\n<li>Effects of toxins and other foreign substances (such as carbon monoxide poisoning, over-counter medications, illicit drugs, etc.)</li>\n</ul>', 'Slide 68 - EMPLOYEE HEALTH AND SOCIAL HABITS', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '136-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:32:51', '2014-11-14 11:32:51', '', 136, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/136-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(221, 1, '2014-11-14 11:34:35', '2014-11-14 11:34:35', '<h3>Aircraft maintainers can take common sense steps to maintain their fitness and health.  In your groups, discuss what these include:</h3>\n[row]\n[column_6]\n<ul class="big_ul">\n<li>Eating regular meals and a well-balanced diet</li>\n<li>Taking regular exercise (exercise sufficient to double the resting pulse rate for 20 minutes, three times a week is often recommended)</li>\n<li>Using Personal Protective Equipment (PPE)</li>\n<li>Using barrier creams\n\nSun precaution\n\nTaking care of each other\n\nStopping smoking.', 'Slide 69 - EMPLOYEE HEALTH AND SOCIAL HABITS', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '137-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:34:35', '2014-11-14 11:34:35', '', 137, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/137-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(222, 1, '2014-11-14 11:35:08', '2014-11-14 11:35:08', '', 'slide_69', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', 'slide_69', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:35:08', '2014-11-14 11:35:08', '', 137, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_69.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(223, 1, '2014-11-14 11:38:52', '2014-11-14 11:38:52', '<h3>When aircraft maintainers go to work, they cannot leave stresses associated with home behind. Domestic stress typically results from major life changes at home, such as: </h3>\n&nbsp;\n<ul class="big_ul">\n<li>Marriage</li>\n<li>Birth of a child</li>\n<li>A son or daughter leaving home</li>\n<li>Bereavement of a close family member or friend</li>\n<li>Divorce</li>\n<li>Family commitments </li>\n</ul>\nâInability to concentrate fully may impact on the maintainerâs task performance and ability to pay due attention to safety.â', 'Slide 72 - DOMESTIC STRESS', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '140-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:38:52', '2014-11-14 11:38:52', '', 140, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/140-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(224, 1, '2014-11-14 11:40:36', '2014-11-14 11:40:36', '<h3>In your groups please list 5 stressors that could lead to stress at work:</h3>\n&nbsp;\n[row]\n[column_6]\n<ul class="big_ul">\n<li>Too much work</li>\nChanging shift patterns</li>\nPersonal problems, family problems</li>\nConflict with managers or colleagues</li>\nPeer pressure</li>\nFatigue</li>\nTime pressure</li>\nEnvironment â too hot too cold</li>\nNoise</li>\nPoor health</li>\nNot taking regular breaks</li>\nLack of rest periods.</li>\n</ul>\n', 'Slide 73 - GROUP TASK', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '141-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:40:36', '2014-11-14 11:40:36', '', 141, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/141-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(225, 1, '2014-11-14 11:41:11', '2014-11-14 11:41:11', '', 'slide_73-a', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', 'slide_73-a', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:41:11', '2014-11-14 11:41:11', '', 141, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_73-a.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(226, 1, '2014-11-14 11:41:23', '2014-11-14 11:41:23', '', 'slide_73-b', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', 'slide_73-b', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:41:23', '2014-11-14 11:41:23', '', 141, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_73-b.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(227, 1, '2014-11-14 11:43:12', '2014-11-14 11:43:12', '<h3>As already discussed one of the potential stressors in maintenance is time pressure:</h3>\n&nbsp;\n<h3>Actual</h3>\n<ul class="big_ul">\n<li>Pressure where clearly specified deadlines are imposed by an external source (e.g. management or supervisors) and passed on to the maintainers</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Perceived </h3>\n<ul class="big_ul">\nWhere maintainers feel that there are time pressures when carrying out tasks, even when no definitive deadlines have been set in stone\n\nSelf-imposed\nEngineers set themselves deadlines to complete work (e.g. completing a task before a break or before the end of a shift)', 'Slide 74 - TIME PRESSURE AND DEADLINES', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '142-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:43:12', '2014-11-14 11:43:12', '', 142, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/142-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(228, 1, '2014-11-14 11:45:26', '2014-11-14 11:45:26', '<h3>As with stress, some time pressure is stimulating and may actually improve task performance:</h3>\n<ul class="big_ul">\n	<li>However, it is almost certainly true that excessive time pressure (either actual or perceived, external or self-imposed), is likely to mean that due care and attention when carrying out tasks diminishes and more errors will be made</li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n<h3 class="blueish" style="text-align: center;">âUltimately, these errors can lead to aircraft incidents and accidentsâ</h3>', 'Slide 75 - TIME PRESSURE AND DEADLINES', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '143-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:45:26', '2014-11-14 11:45:26', '', 143, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/143-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(229, 1, '2014-11-14 11:45:56', '2014-11-14 11:45:56', '', 'slide_75', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', 'slide_75', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:45:56', '2014-11-14 11:45:56', '', 143, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_75.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(230, 1, '2014-11-14 11:48:34', '2014-11-14 11:48:34', '', 'slide_77', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', 'slide_77', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:48:34', '2014-11-14 11:48:34', '', 145, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_77.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(231, 1, '2014-11-14 11:49:57', '2014-11-14 11:49:57', '<h3>Here are some of the thinks that can causes individual fatigue:</h3>\n&nbsp;\n[row]\n[column_6]\n<ul class="big_ul">\n<li>Excessive hours of work</li>\n<li>Insufficient out of hours rest/sleep</li>\n<li>Dehydration</li>\n<li>Organisational</li>\n<li>Poor planning of work</li>\n<li>Insufficient personnel</li>\n<li>Poor shift pattern</li>\n<li>Temperature, humidity, noise.</li>\n</ul>\n[/column_6]\n[column_6]\n<img src="http://localhost/aviation-safety/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/slide_77.png" alt="slide_77" width="255" height="182" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-230" />\n[/column_6]\n[/row]', 'Slide 77 - FATIGUE', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '145-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-11-14 11:49:57', '2014-11-14 11:49:57', '', 145, 'http://localhost/aviation-safety/145-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
